Caisse de dépôt et placement du Québec - Wikipedia





















 






Caisse de dépôt et placement du Québec

From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia


					Jump to:					navigation, 					search

Not to be confused with Caisse des dépôts et consignations.

Caisse de dépôt et placement du Québec





Type

Crown corporation


Industry
Institutional investor


Founded
July 15, 1965


Headquarters
65, rue Sainte-Anne
Quebec City, Quebec, Canada (Main business office located in Montréal)



Key people

Michael Sabia, CEO


Total assets
 $270.7 billion CAD (December 31, 2016)



Number of employees

851 (at December 31, 2015)


Website
www.cdpq.com


Caisse de dépôt et placement du Québec (CDPQ) (lit. Quebec Deposit and Investment Fund, also referred to in English-language media as the Caisse) is an institutional investor that manages several public and parapublic pension plans and insurance programs in Quebec. It was founded in 1965 by an act of the National Assembly under the government of Jean Lesage. It is the second largest pension fund in Canada, after the Canada Pension Plan (CPP).[1] As at December 31, 2016, CDPQ managed net assets of C$270.7 billion invested in Canada and elsewhere.[2] CDPQ is headquartered in Quebec City in the Price building and has its main business office in Montreal at Édifice Jacques-Parizeau.



